  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 우인(虞人) : '
    value: 피관은 피물(皮物)로 만든 갓. 우인은 산림(山林)ㆍ천택(川澤)을 맡아 보는 하급 관리이다. 임금이 우인을 부를 때에는 피관을 보내어 오라고 하는 것인데, 옛날에 제(齊)나라 경공(景公)은 대부(大夫)를 부를 때에 사용하는 정(旌)을 보내어 불렀으므로, 그 우인은 죽음을 각오하고 임금의 부름에 응하지 않았다. 《맹자 등문공(孟子藤文公)》
english:
  title: A Refutation of Liu Zihou's Essay on Preserving the Way
  author: Lee Kyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Liu Zihou wrote an essay saying, "Preserving the Way is not as good as preserving one's official post." But this cannot be the words of a sage—the one who transmitted it must have erred. The leather cap is the possession of the game warden; the object is the measure of the Way. Only by guarding that object, by adhering to its measure, does the Way truly endure. Abandon it, and you abandon the Way itself. An official post is the instrument through which the Way is served. There has never been one who preserved the Way yet lost his post. To say that preserving the Way is inferior to preserving one's post is to lose sight of the very root.

    Liu Zihou's words here are indeed sound. Yet I believe this argument applies only to those of supreme wisdom, not to the teaching a sage would offer to all people universally. Why? If one says, "Preserving one's post is not as good as preserving the Way," then for those of highest wisdom—those who understand that the Way is the root of preserving office, and office the instrument of practicing the Way—they may keep both root and instrument intact, as Liu Zihou suggests. But for those of middling or inferior capacity, ignorant that the Way underlies their duties, chasing vainly after some abstract Way while neglecting their posts, they will soon find their responsibilities abandoned, their work ruined, and calamity upon them—their posts untenable. This would lead them into wrongdoing. How could this be the teaching of a sage?

    But if one understands it as, "Preserving one's post is not as good as preserving the Way," and yet applies himself diligently and faithfully to his duties, then he draws near to the Way indeed. Does the Way not endure? The sage's words—"Preserving the Way is not as good as preserving one's post"—are themselves a teaching about preserving the Way. He merely speaks of what comes first and what comes after. His intention remains unchanged. This is how the sage, in wisdom and gentleness, guides people to seek understanding for themselves. How then can one say the transmitter erred?
  footnotes:
    - 'The leather cap (皮冠) was an ornament worn by minor officials such as the game warden (虞人). The anecdote referenced here comes from the Mencius: when Duke Jing of Qi used a ceremonial banner (旌) to summon a noble, but only a leather cap to summon his game warden, the warden took offense and refused to come, preferring death to such disrespect.'
    - This essay engages with the historical figure Liu Zongyuan (柳宗元, 773-819), a Tang dynasty writer and philosopher, and likely discusses a real or supposed statement about the relative importance of moral cultivation versus fulfilling one's social duties.
